<TITLE> SC cancels Hasina's bail in Bangabandhu Memorial Trust case, trial to go on </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 26 (bdnews24.com)  The Supreme Court Monday cancelled Sheikh Hasina's bail granted by the High Court in a case that charges her with taking Tk 3 crore in bribe from a power company during her days as prime minister and using it to buy a building for Bangabandhu Memorial Trust. The apex court also halted the High Court freeze on the proceedings of the case, clearing way for trial to go on in lower court. The full bench of the Appellate Division headed by chief justice Md Ruhul Amin issued the orders after hearing the petitions of the government and the Anticorruption Commission. Hasina's counsel barrister Fazle Noor Tapash later said to reporters,"The Supreme Court today has stayed that the High Court orders and said the trial of the case will now proceed in the lower court." "We are disappointed with the Supreme Court orders today," he said. The High Court granted Hasina bail in the case on Nov 4 and the case proceedings the same day as well. The government included the case for trial under emergency powers rules on Sept 20. On Oct 28, Hasina in a writ petition challenged in the High Court the legality of the government taking the case under the cover of emergency powers rules for trial . In the same petition, she appealed for bail in the case. The High Court granted former prime minister Hasina bail in the case on Nov 4, and stayed the case proceedings the same day. The government and the ACC on Nov 8 appealed the High Court orders with the Appellate Division. The ACC filed a case on Sept 2 against Awami League chief Hasina, former power and energy secretary Towfique-e-Elahi Chowdhury, former Power Development Board chairman Nooruddin Mahmud Kamal, Summit Industries and Mercantile Corporation Ltd managing director Muhammad Aziz Khan and United Group chairman Hasan Mahmud Raja and two others. The case filed Tejgaon Police Station charged Hasina with accepting donations of Tk 3 crore for the Bangabandhu Memorial Trust in Dhanmondi in 1997 in exchange for granting special facilities to set up three private sector power projects. The government included the case for trial under emergency powers rules on Sept 20. The Awami League chief was arrested by joint forces in her home on July 16 in an extortion case filed by businessman Azam Jahangir Chowdhury and detained in the special jail the same day. bdnews24.com/at
